WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:06.190 --> 00:00:07.490
&gt;&gt; Anne Cecelia Holmes:
It is an honor

00:00:07.490 --> 00:00:11.100
to introduce this evening's
reader, Sandra Beasley.

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:14.180
Sandra is the author of
three poetry collections,

00:00:14.180 --> 00:00:18.710
most recently Count the Waves,
along with I was a Jukebox,

00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:23.460
winner of the Barnard Women Poet's
prize, and Theories of falling,

00:00:23.460 --> 00:00:26.570
winner of the New Issues
Poetry Prize.

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:31.850
Honors for her work include a
2015 NEA Literature Fellowship,

00:00:31.850 --> 00:00:34.300
the Center for Book
Arts Chapbook Prize,

00:00:34.300 --> 00:00:38.320
and two DCCAH Artist Fellowships.

00:00:38.320 --> 00:00:41.970 position:56%
She lives right here, in Washington,
D.C. and is on the faculty

00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:45.210
of the Low-Residency MFA program
at the University of Tampa.

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:48.450
I want to talk just a bit

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:53.050
about Sandra Beasley's most recent
collection, Count the Waves.

00:00:53.050 --> 00:00:58.600
In it, poems create and examine
correspondence over distances,

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:01.570
how the weariness of
travel can code and twist

00:01:01.570 --> 00:01:04.640
and pull at our relationships.

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:09.730
It's like participating in a game
of telephone, but often lonelier.

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:13.670
The end of the receiving line never
gets to meet the original voice,

00:01:13.670 --> 00:01:15.870
or the connection is lost,

00:01:15.870 --> 00:01:19.230
or the preceding participants
have all simply left,

00:01:19.230 --> 00:01:22.590 position:56%
leaving reliability up for question.

00:01:22.590 --> 00:01:24.810
This is when Beasley's poems wildly

00:01:24.810 --> 00:01:28.630
and inventively re-imagine
and retell history.

00:01:28.630 --> 00:01:30.640
They look around and take inventory

00:01:30.640 --> 00:01:34.610
of what deserves consideration
and what doesn't.

00:01:34.610 --> 00:01:38.680
She uses humor in tandem with
vulnerability to play out the ways

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:42.790
in which intimacy can be
both elevated and flattened,

00:01:42.790 --> 00:01:46.780
as in when I say I wish
to correspond with you,

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:52.330
what I mean is I want to bite your
tongue across these many miles.

00:01:52.330 --> 00:01:55.950
Lines like this startle
us, make us laugh,

00:01:55.950 --> 00:01:59.430
and ultimately reshape
our sense of the truth.

00:01:59.430 --> 00:02:02.510
Please join me in welcoming
Sandra Beasley.

00:02:02.510 --> 00:02:19.380
[ Applause ]

