00:03:52.110 --> 00:03:56.570
I went through a period of
my life of about five years

00:03:56.570 --> 00:03:58.710
when I was traveling relentlessly.

00:03:58.710 --> 00:04:02.410
I put about 50,000
plus miles on my car.

00:04:02.410 --> 00:04:05.530
And so in some ways, Count
the Waves is about the way

00:04:05.530 --> 00:04:08.620
that intimacy is both lost and,

00:04:08.620 --> 00:04:11.140
in some ways gained,
over long distances.

00:04:11.140 --> 00:04:15.010 position:56%
We allow ourselves to say things
that perhaps we would not otherwise.

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:17.900
And when I was going through
that period of my life,

00:04:17.900 --> 00:04:21.500
many people mentioned that the
practical thing would be for me

00:04:21.500 --> 00:04:24.860
to move my things into
a storage unit,

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:28.310
accept this nomadic time,
and I couldn't do it.

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:33.130
I could not give up the foot that
was keeping me in Washington,

00:04:33.130 --> 00:04:38.200
D.C. So when I read this
opening poem from the collection,

00:04:38.200 --> 00:04:42.060
which is called Inner Flamingo,
I want you to understand

00:04:42.060 --> 00:04:47.440
that while birds are often
appearing in metaphors in my work,

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:51.300
these are literal flamingos,
these are National Zoo flamingos,

00:04:51.300 --> 00:04:55.480
these are me getting home maybe
once a month, twice a month,

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:58.030
and the first thing I did
on a pretty day was walking

00:04:58.030 --> 00:05:01.540
down to the National Zoo,
taking in the open air aviary,

00:05:01.540 --> 00:05:06.250 position:56%
having quality peacock time,
checking on those teenager cheetahs,

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:10.640
right, and looking at those
flamingos and thinking,

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:18.660 position:56%
what love can I find that anchors me
here the way I want to be anchored?

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:21.290
And I did.

00:05:21.290 --> 00:05:23.710
Inner Flamingo.

00:05:23.710 --> 00:05:32.110
At night my body discovers
her secret geometries,

00:05:32.110 --> 00:05:38.110
inner-flamingo knee hitch,
inner-flamenco arm arch,

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:43.320
Hermes' diagonal of
flight across the mattress.

00:05:43.320 --> 00:05:48.000
The sleeping body is selfish.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:52.430
The sleeping body cannot lie.

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:57.670
Once there was the man from
whom I always woke huddled

00:05:57.670 --> 00:06:00.050
at the bed's edge.

00:06:00.050 --> 00:06:03.800
Then there was a man
who laid his lust

00:06:03.800 --> 00:06:09.200
as a doorknocker at
the small of my back.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:14.920
The first time I laid down
with you, sweat-stuck,

00:06:14.920 --> 00:06:18.270
each onion-ed in the
skin of the other,

00:06:18.270 --> 00:06:24.130
I assumed the unconscious
hours would peel us free.

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:30.900
Yet when sun cracked its eye over
the horizon, we were as we'd been.

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:35.970
And the pink of me cocked
her head, listening.

00:06:40.590 --> 00:06:44.520
As you might imagine in a
collection that chooses to start

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:46.600
out with a poem of lasting love,

00:06:46.600 --> 00:06:49.650
if I tell you that I traveled
relentlessly for 5 years

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:51.660
and 50,000 miles, you might guess

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:54.900
that there was some non
lasting love prior to that.

00:06:55.940 --> 00:07:00.850
And so I'm going to read a
trio of poems that describe

00:07:00.850 --> 00:07:06.380
that through line that you
can locate in this book.

00:07:06.380 --> 00:07:09.120
Fidelity II.

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:11.230
[ Laughter ]

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:19.560 position:56%
In some version, his pericardium was
pierced, the body bleeding water.

00:07:19.560 --> 00:07:23.870
Some say only the usual red.

00:07:23.870 --> 00:07:31.450
In one story, a full moon,
in another, hours of eclipse.

00:07:31.450 --> 00:07:36.510
Where gospels agree is
at the door of the cave

00:07:36.510 --> 00:07:43.030
when a boulder rolls back and
some woman, one Mary or another,

00:07:43.030 --> 00:07:47.500
names that first essential absence.

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:54.470
It is April and he raises
his fears every three days.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:58.740
He brings home a bouquet
of muscular lilies.

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:02.330
He waits for the miracle.

00:08:02.330 --> 00:08:10.730
She calls her name into a cave and
the cave answers with her name.

00:08:14.490 --> 00:08:17.810
In the conversation in
the signing line earlier,

00:08:17.810 --> 00:08:21.840 position:56%
a young gentleman was kind enough to
come up and ask how a poem worked,

00:08:21.840 --> 00:08:23.990
something about my process.

00:08:23.990 --> 00:08:29.240
And I talked about oysters
and how, if you know anything

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:33.040
about the actual anatomy of
real oysters, this little bit

00:08:33.040 --> 00:08:35.990
of irritant grit gets
into the creature.

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:39.830
And for me, that might be an
image, or a phrase, or a question.

00:08:39.830 --> 00:08:43.880 position:56%
And what natural oyster will do is
it'll try to protect itself from it,

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:48.110
so it coats itself, coats that
grit in juice and coats again,

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.750
each layer hardening,
each time, realizing oh,

00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:54.040
I still have not gotten that thing
out of my body, coating it again,

00:08:54.040 --> 00:08:57.670
coating it again, until
the pearl is formed.

00:08:57.670 --> 00:09:00.310
And what I was trying to
communicate is that a lot of times,

00:09:00.310 --> 00:09:03.030
by the time I sit down
to draft the poem,

00:09:03.030 --> 00:09:05.840
I've been working on
the poem for days.

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:09.320
And if I'm lucky, it's one of those
perfect pearls, but usually it's

00:09:09.320 --> 00:09:13.120
like a freshwater pearl, kind of
murky and misshapen, and, you know.

00:09:13.120 --> 00:09:21.440
But that metaphor of an
oyster, that one stays with me.

00:09:21.440 --> 00:09:28.240
Parable. Worries come
to a man and a woman,

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:31.760
small ones, light in the hand.

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:36.470
The man decides to
swallow his worries,

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:39.880 position:56%
hiding them deep and within himself.

00:09:39.880 --> 00:09:45.330
The woman throws hers as far
as she can from the porch.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:48.180
They touch each other, relieved.

00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:53.170
They make coffee and make
plans for the seaside in May,

00:09:53.170 --> 00:10:00.540 position:56%
all the while the worries of the man
take his insides as their oyster,

00:10:00.540 --> 00:10:05.440
coating themselves in juice,
first gastric, then nacreous,

00:10:05.440 --> 00:10:08.280
growing layer upon layer.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:11.610
And in the fields beyond
the wash line,

00:10:11.610 --> 00:10:14.690
the worries of the woman take root,

00:10:14.690 --> 00:10:19.190
stretching tendrils
through the rich soil.

00:10:19.190 --> 00:10:23.460
The parable tells us,
consider the ravens.

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:28.650
But the ravens caw useless
from the gutters of this house.

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:33.980
The parable tells us consider
the lilies, but they shiver

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:37.360
in the side yard, silent.

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:40.400
What the parable does
not tell you is

00:10:40.400 --> 00:10:45.230
that this woman collects
porcelain cats.

00:10:45.230 --> 00:10:50.930
Some big, some small,
some gilded, some plain.

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:57.230
One cat stops doors, another
cups cream, another sugar.

00:10:57.230 --> 00:11:01.360
This man knows they are tacky.

00:11:01.360 --> 00:11:07.130 position:56%
Still when the one that had belonged
to her great aunt fell and broke,

00:11:07.130 --> 00:11:10.840
he held her as she
wept, held her even

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:14.940
after her breath had
lengthened to sleep.

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:19.530
The parable does not
care about such things.

00:11:19.530 --> 00:11:24.310
Worry has come to the
house of a man and a woman.

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:30.430
Their garden yields, greens
gone, corn cowering in its husk,

00:11:30.430 --> 00:11:34.010
he asks himself what will we eat?

00:11:34.010 --> 00:11:38.170
They sit at the table and
open the mail, a bill,

00:11:38.170 --> 00:11:42.490
a bill, a bill, an invitation.

00:11:42.490 --> 00:11:46.780
She turns a salt shaker
cat between her palms

00:11:46.780 --> 00:11:50.410
and asks, but what will we wear?

00:11:50.410 --> 00:11:57.000
He rubs her wrist with his thumb,
he wonders how to offer the string

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.970 position:56%
of pearls now writhing in his belly.

00:12:06.390 --> 00:12:08.650
Fidelity I.

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:16.480
She did not mean to keep the
whisk when she packed the kitchen

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:20.330 position:56%
of the apartment they once lived in.

00:12:20.330 --> 00:12:27.030 position:56%
Night after night, he tried to
emulsify soy sauce and peanut butter

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:32.810
with a fork, before dumping
the tan brown mess on lettuce

00:12:32.810 --> 00:12:39.350
and chicken breast boiled to lumps,
good fat bubbling off to pool

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:41.940
in the hollow of the burner.

00:12:41.940 --> 00:12:49.250
The whisk was an honest gift,
curly cued and white ridged ribbon

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:54.380
from a woman who trusted
overpriced solutions,

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:57.960
to a man who thought
anything could blend

00:12:57.960 --> 00:13:01.860
if he worked his hand hard enough.

00:13:04.830 --> 00:13:09.520
So in addition to that
narrative, there's another sequence

00:13:09.520 --> 00:13:11.150
that threads through
Count the Waves.

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:13.380
And I wanted to read poems
from it, because I think

00:13:13.380 --> 00:13:17.720
that this was the work
that the National Endowment

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:20.760
for the Arts was kind
enough to reward,

00:13:20.760 --> 00:13:23.750
to recognize with a
fellowship, which really,

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:26.080
quite literally, shored up my life.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:28.970
It came at a moment when
I needed the support,

00:13:28.970 --> 00:13:30.710
I needed the encouragement.

00:13:30.710 --> 00:13:33.650
And I continued on this
strange path of trying

00:13:33.650 --> 00:13:35.750
to make a living as a writer.

00:13:35.750 --> 00:13:40.150
In 1853, now this is real,

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:45.350
a write named A.C. Baldwin
published a compendium of phrases,

00:13:45.350 --> 00:13:47.930
and he referenced them by number.

00:13:47.930 --> 00:13:52.420
It was this code for
conversations over long distances.

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:58.360
He called this, this collection,
The Traveler's Vade Mecum.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:04.290
Or, instantaneous letter
writer by mail or telegraph

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:07.120
for the convenience of
persons traveling on business

00:14:07.120 --> 00:14:11.520
or for pleasure and for others
whereby a vast amount of time,

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:13.930
labor and trouble is saved.

00:14:13.930 --> 00:14:20.850 position:56%
So in a collection that was already
destined to be about long distances,

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:25.380
I combed through this
manuscript, in part inspired

00:14:25.380 --> 00:14:26.950
by an outside solicitation.

00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:28.680
There will be a whole anthology

00:14:28.680 --> 00:14:31.720
of Traveler's Vade Mecum
poems out later this fall.

00:14:31.720 --> 00:14:35.780
And I picked the ones
that resonated for me.

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:38.850
So you'll hear, for each
title, an actual line

00:14:38.850 --> 00:14:41.110 position:56%
from the 1853 Traveler's Vade Mecum.

00:14:41.110 --> 00:14:46.400
And then under that, thinking
about this idea of space,

00:14:46.400 --> 00:14:48.970
of intimacy lost and gained.

00:14:53.460 --> 00:14:59.320
The Traveler's Vade
Mecum line 7,671.

00:14:59.320 --> 00:15:02.600
It is no secret here.

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:07.990
Dirt, wrote a British
anthropologist,

00:15:07.990 --> 00:15:11.160
is matter out of place.

00:15:11.160 --> 00:15:17.170
Drop a grape from bowl to
table and we call it dirty.

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:22.220
Drop a grape to the
floor and it is trash.

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:26.500
Bowl, table, these
are ordering agents,

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:30.590
ways to tell the functional
from fallen.

00:15:30.590 --> 00:15:36.720
Skin, tendon, thee
are ordering agents.

00:15:36.720 --> 00:15:42.560
You want to kiss my mouth, but
not the teeth inside my mouth.

00:15:42.560 --> 00:15:48.730
You want to hold my hand, but
not the blood within that hand.

00:15:48.730 --> 00:15:52.850
There is a truth in you, but
it won't be the dirty truth

00:15:52.850 --> 00:15:57.190
until it tumbles into
the air between us.

00:15:57.190 --> 00:16:04.240
In this city, there is always
a long walk home at 7 AM light,

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:07.770
high heels stabbing
the subway grates,

00:16:07.770 --> 00:16:12.780
a walk home past gutters
littered with the non sequitur

00:16:12.780 --> 00:16:19.330
of chicken bones, wings that
once held a dream of flight.

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:28.920
Anybody ever had a person in
your life, and this happens to be

00:16:28.920 --> 00:16:33.230
about a he, but it's not
gendered, who just consumed,

00:16:33.230 --> 00:16:36.530
like kind of locust like, whether
it be emotionally or in terms

00:16:36.530 --> 00:16:39.400
of the cupboard, or just
kind of never kept track

00:16:39.400 --> 00:16:42.410
of the available resources
and just assumed

00:16:42.410 --> 00:16:46.630
that something would always
come up to fill the pot?

00:16:46.630 --> 00:16:50.510
If you've ever encountered
someone like this on your travels,

00:16:50.510 --> 00:16:54.520
you usually end up
writing a poem about them.

00:16:55.700 --> 00:17:00.740
The Traveler's Vade
Mecum line 1,181.

00:17:00.740 --> 00:17:04.530
The calamity is not serious.

00:17:05.830 --> 00:17:11.020
He catches the rain
in his cooking pot.

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:14.110
There's nothing to put
in his cooking pot.

00:17:14.110 --> 00:17:17.540
He places a stone in
the cooking pot.

00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:21.580
He dances by the fire
as the water boils.

00:17:21.580 --> 00:17:27.010
Stone soup, stone soup, he
sings, lend a little garnish,

00:17:27.010 --> 00:17:31.590
he tells our village, soon
you'll each have a bowl.

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:35.590 position:56%
In go the carrot tops, the rosemary,

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:38.590
in goes the ham bone
with lard at lips.

00:17:38.590 --> 00:17:42.130
The children gather,
the strays mewls.

00:17:42.130 --> 00:17:49.500
Sometimes it has to be button soup,
sometimes ax soup, sometimes nail.

00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:52.300
In France, he is a soldier.

00:17:52.300 --> 00:17:56.900
In Portugal, he is a monk
stirring sopa de pedra.

00:17:56.900 --> 00:18:01.800
Wherever he goes he
is the clever man.

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:06.010
Folktale 1548 in the
Aarne-Thompson index.

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:12.190
Not to be confused with his
brothers, Eulenspiegel 1635,

00:18:12.190 --> 00:18:20.260
